<HelpLayout title="Privacy Policy" description="Badger privacy policy — what we store, what leaves your device, and your rights.">
  <h1>Privacy Policy</h1>

  <p><strong>Last updated:</strong> 2026-04-22</p>

  <p>
    Badger is a local-first workout tracker. The canonical copy of your training data
    lives on your device. A pseudonymous mirror is also kept in Google Cloud Firestore
    so the same account can be restored if you reinstall the app. This policy explains
    what is stored where, what leaves the device, and your rights.
  </p>

  <h2>Data stored only on your device</h2>
  <p>The following is stored in a local SQLite database on your phone and is never sent to us:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>Workouts, sets, and exercises (including weight, reps, distance, duration, RPE, RIR, notes, comments).</li>
    <li>Routines, routine days, and predefined sets.</li>
    <li>Body measurements and body-weight history.</li>
    <li>Gyms, machines, attachments, and their links to exercises.</li>
    <li>All app settings, preferences, and the debug log ring buffer.</li>
    <li>The most recent crash report, if Badger terminated unexpectedly. Saved as a plain-text file (<code>crash_report.txt</code>) containing the exception, stack trace, and the last ~500 lines of the in-memory log buffer. Only the latest crash is kept — a new crash overwrites the previous file, and sending it via feedback (see below) deletes it.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Data sent automatically to Firebase / Cloud Firestore</h2>
  <p>
    On first launch, the app initialises Firebase and creates an anonymous Firebase
    Authentication user — a random pseudonymous identifier tied to the device, not to
    your name, email, phone number, or any other personally identifying information.
    After that, the app mirrors your workout data to Google Cloud Firestore under
    that identifier as you use it. The following is sent:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Workouts (date, timestamps, workout-level comment, source routine day, gym).</li>
    <li>Workout exercises (exercise id, order, grouping, rest overrides, tempo, machine/attachment, grip type).</li>
    <li>Workout sets (weight, reps, distance, duration, warmup flag, skipped flag, complete flag, comment, RPE, RIR, sort order).</li>
    <li>Deletions of any of the above.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    On first run a one-time backfill pushes your existing local workout history to
    Firestore; subsequent changes are pushed as they happen. Other local data —
    routines, predefined sets, exercise library edits, body measurements, settings,
    debug logs, and crash reports — is <strong>not</strong> sent to Firestore.
  </p>
  <p>
    Firestore data is subject to Google's privacy practices for Firebase. The
    pseudonymous identifier is not linked to your Google account, email, or any
    other personal profile unless a future version of the app adds sign-in.
  </p>

  <h2>Data that can leave your device only when you initiate it</h2>
  <p>In addition to the automatic mirror above, you can export data manually:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Manual backups</strong> — you tap <em>Manual backup</em> in Settings to open the system share sheet and save a <code>.workout_backup</code> file wherever you choose.</li>
    <li><strong>CSV exports</strong> — workout history CSV exports open the share sheet.</li>
    <li><strong>Debug log exports</strong> — the last ~500 lines of in-memory logs can be exported as a plain-text file via the share sheet.</li>
    <li><strong>Feedback emails</strong> — the Send feedback screen opens your email client with a pre-filled draft to <code>feedback@badger.fit</code>. You review and send it from your own email app. If a crash occurred since the last launch, a toggle offers to attach the stored crash report; you can also attach diagnostic logs. Nothing is sent automatically — you always hand-off to your mail app and press send.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Third parties present in the app</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Google Fonts</strong> (Inter) — fetched at runtime when the app first renders text. Google may log the request as part of its standard font serving.</li>
    <li><strong>Firebase Authentication + Cloud Firestore</strong> — used on every launch for anonymous sign-in and workout sync as described above.</li>
    <li><strong>Google Sign-In + Google Drive API</strong> — scaffolded for future Drive backups. Not currently used.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>What we explicitly do not do</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>No analytics, metrics, or telemetry.</li>
    <li>No advertising or ad-tracking SDKs.</li>
    <li>No user profiling or behavioural tracking.</li>
    <li>No third-party SDKs beyond those listed above.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Your rights</h2>
  <p>
    Deleting the app removes the local copy of your data. The Firestore mirror
    remains under the anonymous identifier that was associated with your install;
    to have that mirror deleted, email
    <a href="mailto:privacy@badger.fit">privacy@badger.fit</a> from the address
    you want us to reply to. If you have emailed us feedback that included personal
    information and want it deleted from our mailbox, email the same address.
  </p>

  <h3>California residents (CCPA/CPRA)</h3>
  <p>
    If you are a California resident, you have the right to know what personal information
    we have collected, to request deletion, and to opt out of the sale or sharing of your
    personal information. We do not sell or share personal information. To exercise these
    rights, email <a href="mailto:privacy@badger.fit">privacy@badger.fit</a>.
  </p>

  <h2>Children</h2>
  <p>Badger is not directed at children under 13 and we do not knowingly collect information from them.</p>

  <h2>Updates</h2>
  <p>
    If we change this policy we will update the <strong>Last updated</strong> date at the top
    and, for material changes, call it out in the app. Continued use of the app after an
    update constitutes acceptance.
  </p>

  <h2>Contact</h2>
  <p>
    Privacy questions: <a href="mailto:privacy@badger.fit">privacy@badger.fit</a><br />
    General: <a href="mailto:hello@badger.fit">hello@badger.fit</a>
  </p>
</HelpLayout>
